git --version

This will return the version of Git that you're running and look something like this:

//(Any version 1.7.10 or higher is fine.)

//Next, configure Git so it knows who to associate your changes to:
Set your name:
git config --global user.name "protocol42"

Now set your email:
git config --global user.email "jhull@protocolrescue.com"

//done 
npm install -g git-it

// open git-it - go to repository
git-it

// create project folder
mkdir hello-world

//To go into that folder:
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa
cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub


//To create a new Git instance for a project:
git init


That's it! It will just return you to a new line. If you want to be double-sure that it's a Git repository, type 

git status

//create local git repository
// mkdir - enter dir - check git status
mkdir hello-world;cd hello-world;git init;git status


// commit to git repository
// write text to file - git add file - git commit added files
echo 'test text'>>README.txt;git add README.txt;git commit -m 'test file'

// return changes made to file
git diff


// add git hub user name to git config 
git config --global user.username protocol42


// add remote server address to local machine 
1.get http from new repository on git hub
https://github.com/protocol42/hello-world.git

2. shuve http up into ' git remote add origin <URLFROMGITHUB> '

git remote add origin https://github.com/protocol42/hello-world.git

//Your local repository now knows where your remote one named 'origin' lives on GitHub's servers.

// push
git push origin master


git remote add origin https://github.com/protocol42/hello-world.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

git remote add origin git@github.com:protocol42/hello-world.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

git-it verify



echo "# hello-world" >> README.md
git init;git add README.md
git commit -m "first commit";git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/protocol42/hello-world.git;
git push -u origin main



echo "# hello-world" >> README.md
git init
git add README.md
git commit -m "first commit"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/protocol42/hello-world.git
git push -u origin main



